In {{ill|Taika (era)|ja|大化|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} 5 (649), on August 13, Mononobe no Sukune Hirokuni enshrined their ancestral deity at the current location in Katsube village of the Mononobe district, naming it "Mononobe Daimyōjin." In the {{ill|Ninju era|ja|仁寿|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} 1 (851), the shrine was granted the Rank of {{ill|Senior Sixth Rank, Upper|ja|正六位上|1=Senior Sixth Rank|lt=Senior Sixth Rank, Upper Grade|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} in January. In {{ill|Gangyō|ja|元慶|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} 6 (882), it received {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank, Lower|ja|従五位下|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.

During the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine received devout support from the {{ill|Rokkaku clan|ja|六角氏|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, the governors of {{ill|Ōmi Province|ja|近江国|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. When the Rokkaku army set out on campaigns, they always used bamboo from the shrine's bamboo grove for their flags. The three-bay nagare-zukuri style honden with cypress bark roofing was rebuilt in {{ill|Meiō|ja|明応|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} 6 (1497) through the contributions of {{ill|Rokkaku Takayori|ja|六角高頼|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.

In the {{ill|Tenshō|ja|元亀|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} era (1570–1573), {{ill|Oda Nobunaga|ja|織田信長|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} deposited 60 oaths from {{ill|Yasu District, Ōmi|ja|野洲郡|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Kurita District, Ōmi|ja|栗太郡|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} at the shrine. In {{ill|Bunroku|ja|文禄|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} 3 (1594), {{ill|Toyotomi Hidetsugu|ja|豊臣秀次|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} donated rice fields and repaired the honden.

During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, the area thrived as the site of the {{ill|Moriyama-juku|ja|守山宿|fr|6=en|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} post town.

In 1913, the honden was designated as a National Specially Protected Building, equivalent to the current designation of {{ill|Important Cultural Property (Japan)|ja|重要文化財|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)|2=ja|3=重要文化財|lt=Important Cultural Property|qq= (Japan)|4=ko|5=일본의_중요문화재|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.

Until the Edo period, the shrine was called "Mononobe Shrine" or "Mononobe Daimyōjin," but it was renamed Katsube Shrine in the early {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治時代|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. In 1931, it was designated as a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.

The shrine includes a preserved {{ill|Chinju no Mori|ja|鎮守の森|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (sacred forest) within its grounds.

The Kenjo Hall and Chūkonhi monument were constructed before World War II to honor local war dead.

