'''Katsube Shrine''' (勝部神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in {{ill|Moriyama, Shiga|ja|守山市|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Moriyama, Shiga|qq=}}, Katsube district, {{ill|Shiga Prefecture|ja|滋賀県|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiga Prefecture|qq=}}. The shrine's official name is "Mononobe-gō Sōja Katsube Shrine" (物部郷総社 勝部神社). Before the war, it was called "Mononobe Shrine," "Mononobe Daimyōjin," or "Katsube Daimyōjin." It was the [[Sōja shrine]] (総社) of the former Mononobe district and held the Rank of a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gōsha|qq=}} under the [[Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines]].

It contrasts with provincial Soja shrines which enshrine all the kami of a province<ref>https://archive.ph/wip/XtZfZ</ref>

== History ==

In {{ill|Taika (era)|ja|大化|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taika (era)|qq=}} 5 (649), on August 13, Mononobe no Sukune Hirokuni enshrined their ancestral deity at the current location in Katsube village of the Mononobe district, naming it "Mononobe Daimyōjin." In the {{ill|Ninju era|ja|仁寿|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninju era|qq=}} 1 (851), the shrine was granted the Rank of {{ill|Senior Sixth Rank, Upper|ja|正六位上|1=Senior Sixth Rank|lt=Senior Sixth Rank, Upper Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Sixth Rank, Upper|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Sixth Rank|qq=}} in January. In {{ill|Gangyō|ja|元慶|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gangyō|qq=}} 6 (882), it received {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank, Lower|ja|従五位下|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Fifth Rank, Lower|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Fifth Rank|qq=}}.

During the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muromachi period|qq=}}, the shrine received devout support from the {{ill|Rokkaku clan|ja|六角氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rokkaku clan|qq=}}, the governors of {{ill|Ōmi Province|ja|近江国|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmi Province|qq=}}. When the Rokkaku army set out on campaigns, they always used bamboo from the shrine's bamboo grove for their flags. The three-bay nagare-zukuri style honden with cypress bark roofing was rebuilt in {{ill|Meiō|ja|明応|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiō|qq=}} 6 (1497) through the contributions of {{ill|Rokkaku Takayori|ja|六角高頼|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rokkaku Takayori|qq=}}.

In the {{ill|Tenshō|ja|元亀|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō|qq=}} era (1570–1573), {{ill|Oda Nobunaga|ja|織田信長|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oda Nobunaga|qq=}} deposited 60 oaths from {{ill|Yasu District, Ōmi|ja|野洲郡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yasu District, Ōmi|qq=}} and {{ill|Kurita District, Ōmi|ja|栗太郡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kurita District, Ōmi|qq=}} at the shrine. In {{ill|Bunroku|ja|文禄|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunroku|qq=}} 3 (1594), {{ill|Toyotomi Hidetsugu|ja|豊臣秀次|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyotomi Hidetsugu|qq=}} donated rice fields and repaired the honden.

During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}, the area thrived as the site of the {{ill|Moriyama-juku|ja|守山宿|fr|6=en|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Moriyama-juku|qq=}} post town.

In 1913, the honden was designated as a National Specially Protected Building, equivalent to the current designation of {{ill|Important Cultural Property (Japan)|ja|重要文化財|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)|2=ja|3=重要文化財|lt=Important Cultural Property|qq= (Japan)|4=ko|5=일본의_중요문화재|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Cultural Property (Japan)|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Cultural Property (Japan)|qq=}}.

Until the Edo period, the shrine was called "Mononobe Shrine" or "Mononobe Daimyōjin," but it was renamed Katsube Shrine in the early {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era|2=ja|3=明治|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}}. In 1931, it was designated as a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gōsha|qq=}}.

The shrine includes a preserved {{ill|Chinju no Mori|ja|鎮守の森|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chinju no Mori|qq=}} (sacred forest) within its grounds.

The Kenjo Hall and Chūkonhi monument were constructed before World War II to honor local war dead.

== Enshrined Deities ==
* '''Primary deity''': Mononobe Futsukami ({{ill|Amenohoakari|ja|天火明命|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amenohoakari|qq=}}, {{ill|Umashimaji|ja|宇麻志間知命|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Umashimaji|qq=}}, {{ill|Futsunushi|ja|経津主神|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futsunushi|qq=}})
* '''Additional Deities''': {{ill|Sumiyoshi Sanjin|ja|住吉三神|1=Sumiyoshi sanjin|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumiyoshi Sanjin|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumiyoshi sanjin|qq=}} and [[Sarutahiko Ōkami]]

